美联储官员 具体表态内容
威廉姆斯 (纽约联储主席) 美国通货膨胀率“仍然太高”，美联储将坚持加息，直到央行实现其2%的通胀目标。
哈克 (费城联储主席) 需要维持25个基点的利率路径，美联储还没有结束加息周期，但可能正在接近。
洛根 (达拉斯联储主席) 美联储的加息周期可能会更长，预计将在“相当长一段时间”继续缩表。
巴尔金 (里士满联储主席) CPI报告大致符合预期，但通胀的惯性和持续性远超预期，其将注重加息的滞后性。
梅斯特 (克利夫兰联储总裁) 在2月初的议息会议上，她就有充足的理由认为需要加息50个基点，新发布的数据并没有改变她的观点。
布拉德 (圣路易斯联储总裁) 不排除支持3月份加息50个基点的可能性，倾向于美联储可以尽快达到5.375%的政策利率峰值。

Citation Purpose Sample Measures Findings Comments
Aksan et al. (2011) To examine effects of navigation secondary tasks to safety errors and cognitive function to driving ability 77 controls, 32 with AD, 39 with Parkinson's disease Battery of tests and an ORDT. Had to memorize a route and navigate, and then identify landmarks while driving (secondary task). Individuals with AD and Parkinson's disease scored worse than controls on all driving measures. Secondary tasks increased driving errors. Speed of processing predicted on-task safety errors after controlling for other factors. Visual sensory function, memory, and set shifting (TMT-B) predicted secondary task performance. All participants were currently driving.
Anderson et al. (2012) To evaluate neuropsychological tests in driving safety risk in individuals with and without disease 185 controls, 40 with AD, 92 with Parkinson's disease, 29 who had a stroke Battery of tests and ORDT Visual-sensory function, memory, visual spatial abilities, speed of processing related to ORDT scores All participants were currently driving.
Berndt, Clark, & May (2008) To assess dementia severity as an indicator of driving performance to determine when driving cessation should occur 117 with dementia (MMSE scores 18 to 30) ORDT and MMSE Those who passed ORDT had higher MMSE scores than those who failed. Drivers who failed ORDT were also older. One third of those with very mild and one half of those with early-stage dementia passed the test. Converted MMSE scores to CDR and had no description of type of dementia.
Carr, Barco, Wallendorf, Snellgrove, & Ott (2011) To develop a screening battery for on-road performance of drivers with dementia 99 with dementia Host of psychological tests and then the dependent variable was a pass/fail standard road test. Used stepwise logistic regression to determine the best variables. Using a combination of the AD-8 total score, CDT, and TMT-A or SBT time predicted accurately the majority of those who would fail the ORDT. All participants were identified as needing a driving evaluation.
Dawson, Anderson, Uc, Dastrup, & Rizzo (2009) To measure association of cognition, visual perception, and motor function in driving safety in AD 40 with early-stage AD (33 men, 7 women), 115 controls (60 men, 55 women) Neuropsychological battery, motor ability, and ORDT Those with AD only had driving and safety errors. A composite score reflecting test performances across multiple cognitive domains was best predictor of driving safety. All participants were currently driving.
Lafont et al. (2010) To identify cognitive tools associated with unsafe driving among older adult drivers of varying cognitive levels 23 with early-stage AD, 20 age- and gender-matched controls, 36 additional drivers without dementia Battery of neuropsychological tests and ORDT Individuals with AD had lower cognitive performances for all time and speed measures and scores worse on the ORDT. The Wechsler Digit Symbol Substitution test score was the best cognitive measure to detect unsafe driving. All participants were currently driving.
